Development Credit Authority (DCA) Data Set Loan Transactions

Author: Bareket Karif

Date: 5 2016

Data source

Date Description:

USAIDs Development Credit Authority (DCA) works with investors, local financial institutions, and development organizations to design and deliver investment alternatives that unlock financing for U.S. Government priorities. USAID guarantees encourage private lenders to extend financing to underserved borrowers in new sectors and regions. This dataset is the complete list of all private loans made under USAIDs DCA since it was established in 1999. To protect the personal information of borrowers and bank partners, all strategic and personal identifiable information was removed.

description of the relevant filds:

  • Transaction Report ID - is the unique number of transaction report
  • Amount (USD) - is the amount of the loan
  • End Date - is the last date the money need to come back
  • Latitude - is the latitude of the borrower
  • Longitude - is the longitude of the borrower
  • Is Woman Owned? - tell us if the owner is woman
  • Is First Time Borrower? - tell us if its the first time of a borrower

Analysis of the data by various criteria

The graph describe the gender of the owner - woman/man

From this graph we can learn that most of the owners is men. This result is not surprising because in most cases men are at management position.

The graph describe if its the first time of a borrower

From this graph we can learn that most of people borrows more then one time. This result is not surprising, because people does not calculate the exact amount they will need correctly, and thus need an extra money loan.

Summary of Conclusions and Recommendations for Further Research

here we can see the statistics of the amount of the loan
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max.     NA's 
##        0      634     1268    22000     2536 25000000        1

From this graph we can learn that most of the people borrows About 20,000.

In conclusion, this report shows that private lenders have common features, such as gender of the owner and the number of times the borrower borrows.

my recommendation for further research, is to use the information collected in this report, and to check the probability of a borrower to be a man/woman. In addition, to check if the investment is worthwhile, i.e, checking if the borrower is worth investing in. finally, investigate if there is a connection between the two of the above.
